I teach online graduate courses for the Professional Development program in technology integration in the classroom.
Given the info collected on this page, this isn't an anonymous survey.

The results of the 'technology in the classroom', 'capturing lectures', and general use of technology from a teaching perspective will be extremely skewed do to the remote nature of many courses during this pandemic. Please take this fact into consideration when compiling the data.

Love ITS and ETO staff. Have always been helpful. Redesign of MyFramingham made webpage more confusing. Break it down with more descriptive headings & subheadings. Link to “mini” point-and- click short video it textual training pop-ups for certain activities /information that one can find on myFramingham.

ETO, IT, and Library staff are all great. Library Resources, especially streaming (e.g. Kanopy, etc.) are dated and for my purposes, pretty useless. The addition of e-Books has been a lifesaver as the physical collections offer slim pickings; the Choice card method of ordering books is helpful, but again - slim pickings. Most of what I would work with is not included and folks balk at buying books. I should like to have a budget for ordering books and select them myself. Finally, Interlibrary loan is problematic and the system not up to par with other institutions- despite the understandable delays due to covid - the notifications don't tell one which text is in. In many cases, I've had to give up and outsource requests for materials. Still, I would really like to know what DID arrive to assess whether it's worth trekking to the library. The renewal process is also super clunky in contrast to other institutions where I've worked.
Interlibrary loan by mail for remote teachers/students and emerita professors.  Offered at comparable schools,
The course I teach has so far been very self-contained, with few links to the Library or what it offers
no
I think the IT and library services at FSU are the best!

I create my own lessons for research strategies and using the library's resources. I'd like to be able to work with the library staff more directly, but past experiences with library instruction haven't been well adapted to my students' projects and needs.

I think that the helpdesk and ETO need more staff.  Normally, I have no problem receiveing responses or training from them.  This year, some of my "tickets" submitted through the Self-service portal have gone unanswered for weeks to a month or partially answered (tried something, it did not work, reported the lack of result, no response for weeks).  When you are trying to teach remotely, this is a real problem.
Survey too long.  Could be shortened.

The Library staff is excellent.  They always provide a high level of service to myself and my students.  I admire the student workers at the IT Help Desk as well--sometimes, they know exactly how to help; sometimes there is a delay until a more knowledgeable employee is able to assist.  Given our funding realities, this is an still an admirable model for providing tech support to the campus.

I use an embedded librarian in my graduate class. She is extremely kind and responsive. But, she has no experience with the integration of the turnitin.com tool and how it works in research papers. This limits her ability to help my students through 50% of their prep in final research papers. I really believe all library staff should fully be training in how www.turnitin.com works so that they can truly help students through the research paper process. I teach fully asynchronous so some tools I am very familiar with but don't use at F.S.U. Thanks.

We need more physical books and journals (physical and electronic), easy access to them, and staff who are able to help students identify and locate those resources for their research. In terms of access, we need to invest resources that will allow FSU eventually to join a serious university library consortium. Students desperately need those resources. We need *less* emphasis on cafes and other social spaces, which just duplicate what is already available elsewhere on campus; precious resources should be diverted away from  those initiatives. Finally: we need to ensure that library staff are working in a healthy built environment and not exposed to dangerous toxins.
Kanopy is not useful but there are other more commercial streaming services like Netflix, Hulu, Amazon Prime which would be.

RAM Search has been a detriment to instruction because of the way it collapses all context for search results. Students have a very difficult time figuring out what resources are useful and appropriate for a given assignment.

Hedda Monaghan is the single best staff member at the Whittemore Library. She is profoundly knowledgeable and helpful.

IT Self-Service seems like it works fine, but IT staff has a tendency to close tickets without actually paying attention to whether the user has solved his/her problem.
IT Helpdesk tickets are closed after certain number of days automatically even without resolving the issue(s).

I don't know what a lot of the items you asked about actually do, so I don't know if I would use them or not (for example: OneDrive)
I teach studio technical design classes, so do not use the library, but I think the staff is wonderful!
While the circulation and reference staff are helpful, our library is sorely lacking in resources, both digital and physical. This is an impediment for student and faculty research.
no   Your survey is too long--too many questions

I have had the same ITS-provided laptop since I started working here.  
It is time to get a new one.

My comments about IT help: while the students are very friendly, they usually are not able to address my concerns because I have usually exhausted all of the easy answers. Faculty need to be able to talk to a full-time, non-student staff member, without having to go through the students.
Blackboard Collaborate is very clunky and challenging to work with.
Well, the list of age, college, gender, ethnicity and so on would allow all faculty to be identified individually. Whoa! Just ask my name, dude.
Thanks!!
Create a briefer survey

It's hard to answer some of these questions. Overall, staff in ETO, IT, Library are all very reliable and knowledgeable. While I get frustrated with an inability to access articles in journals in my field, that is not any one person's fault. I would love training on data storage. I have different onedrive and google cloud accounts and I have trouble moving between them and keeping track of what gets automatically saved. A tutorial one-on-one or in a workshop on getting the most out of OneDrive would be helpful. Also, another one on GoogleDrive would perhaps be even more useful. Thanks!
you need a dedicated macOS/iOS support staff.
ETO is awesome and so are the research librarians!

How a smart classroom at the rooms I have taught at FSU is defined completely different from other universities I have taught. I was very surprised what was not included in the room when I arrived 8 years ago.
thank you, and please share the results with the FSU community
I really really really don't like Blackboard. It feels like I'm online in 1997.

I taught for 35 years but haven't taught for three years.  Administer a graduate program. I answered questions about myself.  I don't use these services directly but the faculty in my program does.

I used Library Archives when I taught and had an excellent experience.
Helpdesk may not have the answers but they ALWAYS find someone to answer me questions.
ETO staff is wonderful - everyone of them.  They are smart, engaged, responsive, and a joy to work with.
If I don't know how to use a service, it is not because of your staff; it is on me.
I have not used the library resources but I am desiring to learn more

As a visiting professor I teach one postgraduate course per semester. I enjoy making my contribution to student education. Most of this is not applicable to my experience and role within  the university
